{"cursor":"3445","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'HernÃ¡n BÃ¼chi Buc' (born March 6, 1949) is a Chilean economist and politician.\nHe served as Minister of the Treasury under the government of Augusto Pinochet\nbetween 1985 and 1989.\n\nAfter the recession of the early 1980s, BÃ¼chi's appointment as Finance\nMinister in 1985:\n\n...marked the beginning of economic recovery. BÃ¼chi's strategy was\nto create the financial conditions for stable, export-led growth and to\nreorganize the productive structures of the export sector. Control of public\nspending, periodic devaluations, and incentives for domestic savings, foreign\ninvestment and the repatriation of capital gradually brought inflation down to\n12 per cent by 1989, the lowest rate in Latin America. A vigorous campaign to\nsell parcels of the public debt to private investors in exchange for shares in\nChilean industries reduced the nation's debt burden by over $4\nbillion...Economic growth averaged between 5 per cent and 6 per cent in 1985-8,\nthe highest rate in the region. Edwin Williamson, The Penguin History of\nLatin America (Penguin Books, 1992), pp. 508-9.\n\nIn the 1989 Chilean presidential election BÃ¼chi stood for the centre-right\nDemocracy and Progress Party. BÃ¼chi's campaign hired a former public relations\nadviser to former British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, Timothy\nBell. Andy Beckett, Pinochet in Piccadilly. Britain and Chile's Hidden\nHistory (Faber and Faber, 2002), p. 217. BÃ¼chi came second with 2,051,975\nvotes (29.40%). However he \"received more support from women than men in 59 of\nthe 60 electoral districts, the exception being in southernmost district of\nMagallanes, where his support was about equal between the sexes\". [http://j-\nournals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&aid=259965 Paul H.\nLewis, 'The 'Gender Gap' in Chile', Journal of Latin American Studies (2004),\n36: 719-742.]\n\nIn 1996, he wrote a book detailing his experience as Minister of the\nTreasury of Chile during 1985-1989, called\n[http://www.transformamericas.org/], where he discusses in step-by-step\ndetail the entire liberalization process of the Chilean economy, and the\nrole he played in it. It was translated into English in 2009.\n","linknr":111,"url":"Hernán_Büchi","recorded":1375066063,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Hern%C3%A1n_B%C3%BCchi&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Hern%C3%A1n_B%C3%BCchi&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Chile","/wiki/Military_government_of_Chile_(1973%E2%80%931990)","/wiki/Augusto_Pinochet","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Chilean_presidential_election,_1989","/wiki/Alliance_for_Chile","/wiki/Margaret_Thatcher","/wiki/Timothy_Bell,_Baron_Bell","#cite_note-2","/wiki/Magallanes_and_Ant%C3%A1rtica_Chilena_Region","#cite_note-3","/w/index.php?title=The_Economic_Transformation_of_Chile:_A_Personal_Account&action=edit&redlink=1","http://www.transformamericas.org/","/w/index.php?title=Hern%C3%A1n_B%C3%BCchi&action=edit&section=1","/wiki/Crisis_of_1982","/wiki/El_ladrillo","/wiki/Sergio_de_Castro","/w/index.php?title=Hern%C3%A1n_B%C3%BCchi&action=edit&section=2","#cite_ref-1","#cite_ref-2","#cite_ref-3","http://journals.cambridge.org/action/di